      {
        "id": "59a66a73976e21a008ac5ed4a2d7b556f2782cdc",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5305,
          "name": "Pramod Jamkhedkar",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "pramod@research.att.com",
          "username": "pramod.jamkhedkar"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-03-26 05:50:35.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\n> (4 comments)\nThe reason I use JAXB instead fo GSON is that A&AI POJOS are created  from .xsd files using @XMLElement and not @SerializedName. Not sure if GSON can unmarshall such objects.  I tried GSON first but somehow kept getting error in unmarshalling the JSON into A&AI objects. \n\nAlso, I am deprecating the file AaiCqInventoryResponseItem (I will update the patch). In AaiCqresponse, I am storing the Aai custom query results as a collection of Objects. Which I typecast appropriately when returning them back via AaiCqResponse's methods. \n\nI will fix the POM file.",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "cc9d1ca70ad6cb7bb55974c451becb74b02d0443",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 477,
          "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
          "username": "jhh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-03-26 14:17:23.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5: -Code-Review\n\nthanks for the explanation Pramod, if you can fix the pom.xml and the jaxbcontext from my side.",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "759994e1fbc6fa6b3d1709907841ef70b5189e73",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5305,
          "name": "Pramod Jamkhedkar",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "pramod@research.att.com",
          "username": "pramod.jamkhedkar"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-03-27 04:51:30.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\n> (1 comment)\n > \n > What code coverage are you getting? You could also just add throws\n > to the tests.\n\nI cannot do that. Most of these tests have two exceptions (IOException and JAXBException)\n1. If I add two throws to the method definition, SONAR doesn't allow that.  It allows only one exception to be thrown. It suggests creation of a new exception class. \n2. If I catch fail for both these exceptions for each method, I will have write 22 more tests, in addition to  the existing 11 tests. \nWhat do you suggest?",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "023a37d8c8c748f9209dfe968f713918d2bbf571",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5305,
          "name": "Pramod Jamkhedkar",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "pramod@research.att.com",
          "username": "pramod.jamkhedkar"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-03-27 05:04:12.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\n> (2 comments)\n\nIn addition to my previous response on exceptions:\n1. The IOException introduced only because I open a sample file in JUNIT test. It is not thrown by the associated JAVA  class which is tested by the JUNIT. \n2. JAXBException results only because of incorrect JAXB configuration. I don't think it results because of any issue with the input data -- in which case you just get a null for that object.",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
